l" SIZE=1>(</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#ffffff>5/14/01</FONT> <FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#ffffff>11:32:37 am</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>)<BR></FONT><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>Community Supporter</FONT><BR></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Terea</font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Like I posted, my fear experience as soloing tank happened about couple of weeks ago. With good taunting, it is easy to take exp in multi-group raids.<br>
<br>
And to suggest that a lone warrior would need to do most of damage to get the kill, well... that's just hilarious. I really can't see how solo warrior can do most exp against mob that has 10-16k HP when other groups are pounding it too.<br>
<br>
--<br>
<br>
I personally believe that the exp giver formula takes all persons in your group, checks their aggro-rating, makes an average out of those ratings and then compares that average to rest of the groups' average. <br>
<br>
Thus, if you have a cleric in your group that didn't have to heal, a ranger that was afk and an enchanter that didn't have to do anything for that mob... their average is pulling your average down. On the other hand, if you have full blown melee group with cleric healing and you as wiz blasting... everyone is getting aggro points. And... if you are solo, there is no one in your group to raise or lower your average.<br>
<br>
Some good ones to get in group to get high aggro points: shaman slowing mobs, cleric CHealing (not using new cele-heal types), enchanter tashing and especially crippling, and of course a wiz... using discords <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
But that's just personal belief. Your view might differ.<br>
<br>
